LEGIONELLOSIS - SPAIN: (VALENCIA)
*********************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 13 Mar 2015
Source: Entorno Inteligente [in Spanish, trans. Kathryn Soderholm, edited]
http://www.entornointeligente.com/articulo/5304295/El-brote-de-legionela-de-Benidorm-ya-suma-seis-afectados-13032015


The Valencia Department of Health has recorded a new case of legionellosis in Benidorm, which raises the number of related cases to 6 so far. Of these, 4 patients have been admitted to the Marina Baixa Hospital in Vila-Joiosa, where they are in stable condition. They all have the common history of frequenting the sports stadium of Palau d'Esports l'Illa in Benidorm.

The Center for Public Health of Benidorm continues epidemiological and environmental research and has proceeded to schedule cleaning and disinfection per regulations. When the investigation is complete, the situation will be evaluated to ensure that the stadium will re-open in the absence of risk.

The Department of Health reminds people that legionellosis is an infectious disease of environmental origin, produced by bacteria. It is transmitted by air, through inhalation of contaminated aerosolized water, such as from showers, toilets, and cooling tower water. They also note that person-to-person transmission has not been demonstrated.

The most common clinical presentation is pneumonia, which includes respiratory symptoms, fever, and headache. Legionellosis may also produce general symptoms such as fatigue, malaise, and muscle aches. It has an incubation period of 2 to 10 days.

For patients with legionellosis there is a well-established treatment, but there are no preventive medicines or vaccines. It is not necessary to see a doctor after having frequented the same place as the sick patients; medical attention should only be sought if symptoms suggestive of the disease develop.

--
