[For discussions of legionnaires' disease, see my comments in prior ProMED-mail posts listed in the see also's below.

Genotyping of isolates has become a helpful tool to establish transmission pathways. The predominance of one genotype of _Legionella_ isolated from patient specimens would suggest transmission from a common source. Because _Legionella_ may be found in environmental samples without linkage to any cases of legionellosis, the actual causative infectious reservoir can be confirmed by matching the genotype of clinical and environmental isolates (see http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC86783/ and http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2730281/).

However, genotyping is often difficult in legionellosis outbreaks, because the diagnosis is frequently made only on the basis of urinary _Legionella pneumophila_ serogroup 1 antigen testing or serology rather than isolation of the organism from cultures of respiratory tract specimens. Consequently, clinical isolates are often not available for genotyping.

Benidorm, with a population of 73 768 in 2013, is a coastal town in the province of Alicante, in the southern part of the Valencian Community of eastern Spain, on the Western Mediterranean (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benidorm). Formerly a small fishing village, Benidorm is known for its hotel industry, beaches, and skyscrapers and is reported to be Europe and Spain's biggest holiday resort, with 5 million tourists per year.

The news report does not say if the cases of legionellosis were local residents or tourists. According to the US CDC, more then 20 percent of all legionnaires' disease reported to the CDC is travel-associated (http://www.cdc.gov/legionella/health-depts/travel-identify-report.html). Travelers typically disperse to their homes widely separated from one another and perhaps at a very great distance from the source of infection before developing symptoms, so that a cluster of cases of legionnaires' disease in other travelers associated with the same source may not be noticed. A travel history is essential and should be actively sought from patients with community-acquired pneumonia, and _Legionella_ testing should be performed for those who have traveled in the 2 weeks before onset of symptoms. Cases of travel-associated legionnaires' disease need to be reported to the appropriate authorities to be able to detect these outbreaks. - Mod.ML

Maps of Spain can be seen at http://spain.europemaps.info/spain_map.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3233796,9542. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3233796,9542.]
